61
00:04:17,840 --> 00:04:19,796
Just stay straight till I get back.

62
00:04:19,880 --> 00:04:21,836
Put me in your filing cabinet.

63
00:04:21,920 --> 00:04:25,549
I'll spend the next two weeks reading
all the cobblers you write about me!

64
00:04:26,280 --> 00:04:27,760
- Peter, this is Trevor.
- Hello.

65
00:04:27,795 --> 00:04:29,716
What can I do for you, Harry?

66
00:04:29,800 --> 00:04:32,758
- Well, I brought Trevor.
- You mean, this Trevor?

67
00:04:32,840 --> 00:04:35,673
Yeah. His case notes
will be round later in a lorry!

68
00:04:35,760 --> 00:04:37,796
Have you brought Trevor for admission?

69
00:04:37,880 --> 00:04:40,678
- We've just come from court!
- I know nothing about this.

70
00:04:40,760 --> 00:04:42,591
- It's a telephone referral.
- When?

71
00:04:42,680 --> 00:04:44,591
Four, five days ago.

72
00:04:44,680 --> 00:04:47,558
Oh, er, yes... Wait there.

73
00:04:49,200 --> 00:04:51,270
How'd you know I was coming
five days ago?

74
00:04:51,360 --> 00:04:52,315
I didn't.

75
00:04:52,400 --> 00:04:55,472
- I only went to court this morning.
- It's common procedure!

76
00:04:55,560 --> 00:04:58,711
Come through, Harry, Trevor.
See if we can't sort this out.

77
00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:00,756
Come on, bald-brain.

78
00:05:00,840 --> 00:05:03,877
We'll find you a place,
even if we have to pay for it!

79
00:05:05,320 --> 00:05:07,276
<i>(phone ringing)</i>

80
00:05:07,360 --> 00:05:09,874
Harry, Trevor is
a telephone referral, is he?

81
00:05:09,960 --> 00:05:11,439
Right.

82
00:05:12,240 --> 00:05:13,878
Hello, Peter Clive.

83
00:05:13,960 --> 00:05:16,633
Beep-beep-beep-beep!
Hello, Peter Clive.

84
00:05:17,520 --> 00:05:19,192
Terry. Yeah. Yeah, yeah.

85
00:05:19,280 --> 00:05:22,078
Yeah, she's still here.
No, nothing's planned.

86
00:05:22,160 --> 00:05:25,789
No. Er... can you hold on
two ticks, Terry? Good.

87
00:05:25,880 --> 00:05:28,633
Harry, your message
isn't recorded in the log.

88
00:05:28,720 --> 00:05:30,676
- Terry's not expected.
- Trevor!

89
00:05:30,760 --> 00:05:34,070
Oh, Trevor. That makes things
very difficult for us to sort out.

90
00:05:34,160 --> 00:05:36,116
- Impossible, I'd say, Peter.
- Yeah.

91
00:05:36,200 --> 00:05:39,112
Just remembered, I left the care order
round at the court.

92
00:05:39,200 --> 00:05:42,317
<i>- Can't admit him, then.
- (Trevor) When can I go to the Jobcentre?</i>

93
00:05:42,400 --> 00:05:44,630
- Where is it, anyway?
- Can I call you back?

94
00:05:44,720 --> 00:05:46,676
What brought this on?

95
00:05:46,760 --> 00:05:49,877
This place is full of wankers.
I'd rather work than be here!

96
00:05:49,960 --> 00:05:52,554
Look, Peter, can't we
do something with Trevor...

97
00:05:52,640 --> 00:05:55,108
...and then you and me
can have a sort-out?

98
00:05:55,200 --> 00:05:59,193
All right. I'll pass you on to someone else,
if you feel OK about that.

99
00:05:59,280 --> 00:06:02,397
- Don't need me, do you?
- I just want to get down the Jobcentre.

100
00:06:02,480 --> 00:06:04,311
<i>(Peter) Come through.</i>

101
00:06:04,400 --> 00:06:06,675
Back in two ticks, Harry.

102
00:06:06,760 --> 00:06:08,955
- Watch your step, smartarse.
- Bollocks!

103
00:06:09,040 --> 00:06:13,192
- What's this about the Jobcentre?
- Magistrate told me to get a bleedin' job.

104
00:06:13,280 --> 00:06:16,078
I'm Peter Clive,
one of two deputy superintendents.

105
00:06:16,160 --> 00:06:20,119
I'll link you up with your key worker
or house-parent - if we can find them!

106
00:06:20,200 --> 00:06:23,397
They'll fill in your entry form with you,
organise a room.

107
00:06:23,480 --> 00:06:27,553
We've got things like bike workshops,
evening groups, Red Rover days.

108
00:06:27,640 --> 00:06:31,838
Oh, we need to have a little conference
with you about your contract.

109
00:06:37,520 --> 00:06:40,432
I don't like that bed - there's a draught.
I want that one.

110
00:06:40,560 --> 00:06:42,676
- I'm in this bed!
- I know you are.

111
00:06:42,760 --> 00:06:45,320
- You got a swastika on your head.
- I know I have.

112
00:06:45,400 --> 00:06:47,755
I'll sell it to you.

113
00:06:47,840 --> 00:06:52,595
- What's this bollocks about a contract?
- It's Pete Clive. He makes you do it.

114
00:06:52,680 --> 00:06:54,989
- He's a wanker.
- Oh, he's a prick.

115
00:06:55,080 --> 00:06:58,550
You have to promise to behave,
get to school on time and things.

116
00:06:58,640 --> 00:07:00,596
Do it in your own writing and sign it.

117
00:07:00,680 --> 00:07:03,513
- What school?
- I still go to my proper school.

118
00:07:03,600 --> 00:07:05,556
I've been suspended, so I'm back.

119
00:07:05,640 --> 00:07:08,473
- So why aren't you there today?
- Infection in my ear.

120
00:07:08,560 --> 00:07:10,516
My case conference comes up next week.

121
00:07:10,600 --> 00:07:12,989
- Then I might get out.
- They're all wankers.

122
00:07:13,080 --> 00:07:15,036
- Who?
- This lot here.

123
00:07:15,120 --> 00:07:17,111
Hey, what's that?

124
00:07:17,200 --> 00:07:19,156
- Don't you know?
- No.

125
00:07:20,560 --> 00:07:23,074
'Ere, you can have this bed if you want.

126
00:07:23,160 --> 00:07:25,116
No, thanks.

127
00:07:26,880 --> 00:07:28,836
I'll stay over here.

128
00:07:34,960 --> 00:07:37,269
- That's just for the bus?
- That's right.

129
00:07:37,360 --> 00:07:40,477
- What about pocket money?
- You've only just got here.

130
00:07:40,560 --> 00:07:43,358
It's not been fixed yet.
I don't know how much you get.

131
00:07:43,440 --> 00:07:46,955
- Same as everybody else?
- You have damages to pay, don't you?

132
00:07:47,040 --> 00:07:49,349
For the broken window.

133
00:07:49,440 --> 00:07:51,715
- I need some pocket money.
- What for?

134
00:07:51,800 --> 00:07:56,271
If you're just going down to the Jobcentre
and back you won't need pocket money.

135
00:07:56,360 --> 00:07:58,669
You go straight there and back again.

136
00:07:58,760 --> 00:08:02,355
- What if I don't make it back for lunch?
- It won't take that long.

137
00:08:02,440 --> 00:08:05,238
If it was up to me,
you wouldn't be going at all!

138
00:08:14,400 --> 00:08:16,356
They might send me for a job!

139
00:08:25,840 --> 00:08:28,912
Here's an extra pound -
against your pocket money!

140
00:08:53,800 --> 00:08:55,756
Where we going?

141
00:09:17,360 --> 00:09:18,918
Get in.

142
00:09:27,280 --> 00:09:29,236
Remember this?

143
00:09:30,560 --> 00:09:32,516
<i>(starts car)</i>

144
00:09:32,600 --> 00:09:34,556
<i>(revs engine)</i>

145
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:54,956
Evo-Stik.

146
00:10:23,280 --> 00:10:25,236
Stay here.

147
00:10:25,600 --> 00:10:27,556
I feel sick!

148
00:11:00,080 --> 00:11:02,036
Oi! What's this say?

149
00:11:06,600 --> 00:11:09,319
"Supermarket, 23.55 per week."

150
00:11:10,360 --> 00:11:12,316
That's... 50p an hour.

151
00:11:13,200 --> 00:11:15,156
- Bollocks!
- Yeah.

152
00:11:18,680 --> 00:11:20,955
You ain't supposed to take the cards.

153
